I reviewed all issues tagged as features and didn't find any requesting what I'm looking for.

I'd like to make it easier to customize Bootstrap, and do that in a clean way that can be incorporated into a build process. The way I see it, there are primarily two things that somebody might do to customize their copy of Bootstrap:
1. Edit some variables. This is fairly easy; I do this by importing `bootstrap.less` in my own `project.less`, and then declaring the variables that I need to modify.
2. Remove some modules. I currently do this by:
   - Copying `bootstrap.less` to my project.
   - Commenting out the imports that I do not need from `bootstrap.less`.
   - Importing this modified `bootstrap.less` into my `project.less`, as above.
   - I run the LESS processor to compile `project.less`, adding the Bootstrap source path (like `bower_components/bootstrap/less`) to the include paths (so it can find the files referenced from `bootstrap.less`.)

I have an idea for simplifying the second scenario. How about we use variables to control whether each module is included or not? We could use [CSS guards in LESS](http://lesscss.org/features/#css-guards-feature) for this. In each file that's imported from `bootstrap.less`, we could enclose the code in a guard like this:

```
& when (@include-grid = true) {

//
// Grid system
// --------------------------------------------------

// ... the rest of grid.less ...

}
```

We'll have to add a bunch of these `@include-xxx: true;` declarations in `variables.less` or similar.

With this in place, I'll then be able to just import `bootstrap.less` into my `project.less` from a copy of the unmodified Bootstrap, and declare the modules that I do not need like this:

```
@include-glyphicons: false;
@include-grid: false;
```

That would make for a fairly clean and easy build with my customizations built-in.

P.S. I wrote a [blog post](http://www.nikhildabas.com/blog/2013/07/customizing-bootstrap-with-a-build-process) about the process that I currently use.

