It might be worth considering an option for styling tables where the inside of the table has borders for both rows and columns, but the outside of the table has no border. One possible name for this would be: `.table-bordered-inside`. One purpose for this particular style is to retain the inside borders while reducing the non-data ink noise coming from the outside border.

An example of what I mean can be seen in this fiddle: 
http://jsbin.com/hudaqowi/2/edit?html,css,output

``` css
.table-bordered-inside {
  border: 0;
}

.table-bordered-inside>thead>tr>th, 
.table-bordered-inside>tbody>tr>th, 
.table-bordered>tfoot>tr>th, 
.table-bordered-inside>thead>tr>td, 
.table-bordered-inside>tbody>tr>td, 
.table-bordered-inside>tfoot>tr>td  {
   border: 1px solid #ddd;
   border-left: 0;
}

.table-bordered-inside>thead>tr>th:last-child, 
.table-bordered-inside>tbody>tr>th:last-child, 
.table-bordered>tfoot>tr>th:last-child, 
.table-bordered-inside>thead>tr>td:last-child, 
.table-bordered-inside>tbody>tr>td:last-child, 
.table-bordered-inside>tfoot>tr>td:last-child {
  border-right: 0;
}

.table-bordered-inside>tbody>tr:last-child td, 
.table-bordered-inside>tfoot>tr:last-child td {
  border-bottom: 0;
}
```

